00:03:05.059 --> 00:03:07.940
as well as the HR analytics programs.

00:03:07.940 --> 00:03:09.380
But super passionate about this.

00:03:09.380 --> 00:03:12.259
I wish we were big enough to have someone like Dan

00:03:12.259 --> 00:03:14.179
as a data steward,

00:03:14.179 --> 00:03:16.419
but I think it'll be nice to see the balance of a company

00:03:16.419 --> 00:03:19.899
with that infrastructure versus kind of where we have to

00:03:19.899 --> 00:03:21.500
just pull it from other places.

00:03:23.220 --> 00:03:24.339
Thank you both so much

00:03:24.339 --> 00:03:26.699
for kicking off this conversation today.

00:03:26.699 --> 00:03:29.899
And I know Dan, you're going to share a little bit with us

00:03:29.899 --> 00:03:33.339
first about what data stewardship actually means

00:03:33.339 --> 00:03:35.740
before we jump into the discussion too.

00:03:36.940 --> 00:03:39.059
Yeah, and just a quick disclaimer here

00:03:39.059 --> 00:03:42.300
is that views that I express are my own

00:03:42.300 --> 00:03:45.300
and don't necessarily represent those of my company.

00:03:45.300 --> 00:03:48.460
But I want to talk a little bit about data stewardship here.

00:03:48.460 --> 00:03:52.020
When I talk about data stewardship,

00:03:52.020 --> 00:03:54.020
people often ask, is this data governance?

00:03:54.020 --> 00:03:54.979
Is this data stewardship?

00:03:54.979 --> 00:03:57.100
What's the difference here?

00:03:57.100 --> 00:03:58.820
And my joke that I always say

00:03:58.820 --> 00:04:01.059
is that no one likes data governance.

00:04:02.380 --> 00:04:04.059
Whether you're an analyst or an executive,

00:04:04.059 --> 00:04:07.259
everyone thinks it's overkill, it's overhead.

00:04:07.259 --> 00:04:08.259
We don't need that.

00:04:08.259 --> 00:04:10.259
Why are you telling me what to do?

00:04:10.259 --> 00:04:12.860
So very quickly in my journey, I said,

00:04:12.860 --> 00:04:15.539
we need to change how we think about this

00:04:15.539 --> 00:04:16.540
and really think about this

00:04:16.540 --> 00:04:18.420
as the individual owners of the data,

00:04:18.420 --> 00:04:20.459
individual people who work with the data

00:04:20.459 --> 00:04:23.299
and how we steward our own information.

00:04:23.299 --> 00:04:24.899
So this change to data stewardship

00:04:24.899 --> 00:04:27.619
is really with that in mind.

00:04:29.660 --> 00:04:30.500
Internally at Biogen,

00:04:30.500 --> 00:04:33.179
I run a community of practice around data stewardship.

00:04:33.179 --> 00:04:36.220
And we did a crowdsourcing exercise last year

00:04:36.220 --> 00:04:38.179
to come up with what are the best practices.

00:04:38.179 --> 00:04:39.540
And so what I have on the screen

00:04:39.540 --> 00:04:42.220
is the best practices that came out of that work.

00:04:43.140 --> 00:04:44.339
And I'll just talk to it quickly

00:04:44.339 --> 00:04:47.220
and I think Jamie can just pop in with some comments

00:04:47.220 --> 00:04:48.299
as we go through it.

00:04:49.859 --> 00:04:50.980
I'll start on the left,

00:04:50.980 --> 00:04:53.380
which is create data that will be used.

00:04:53.380 --> 00:04:55.980
I know this sounds kind of obvious,

00:04:55.980 --> 00:04:57.779
but it's really important to know

00:04:57.779 --> 00:05:00.299
that whatever you're creating as a data scientist

00:05:00.299 --> 00:05:03.339
or whatever as an analyst is going to be used later on.

00:05:03.339 --> 00:05:05.500
So you want to leave that in a state

00:05:05.500 --> 00:05:07.260
where it can be picked up and used.

00:05:07.260 --> 00:05:09.299
So you want to use well-defined standards,

00:05:09.299 --> 00:05:11.459
templates, metadata to make sure

00:05:11.459 --> 00:05:14.299
that whatever you're creating out of the data

00:05:14.619 --> 00:05:17.339
is able to be picked up and used later on.

00:05:19.140 --> 00:05:20.700
From there, I can go underneath,

00:05:20.700 --> 00:05:24.019
which is have clear roles and responsibilities.

00:05:25.059 --> 00:05:26.299
There's always a little bit of question,

00:05:26.299 --> 00:05:27.339
a little bit of finger pointing.

00:05:27.339 --> 00:05:28.179
Is this your job?

00:05:28.179 --> 00:05:29.019
Is this my job?

00:05:29.019 --> 00:05:30.820
Is this their job?

00:05:30.820 --> 00:05:31.980
Who's doing these things?

00:05:31.980 --> 00:05:33.899
Who's accountable for data access?

00:05:33.899 --> 00:05:37.420
Who's accountable for standardization of data?

00:05:37.420 --> 00:05:40.100
And more clarity that you can add here, the better.

00:05:40.940 --> 00:05:43.619
So I think this is worthwhile to go through

00:05:44.459 --> 00:05:47.700
and make sure that nothing falls in between the cracks.

00:05:47.700 --> 00:05:49.540
And then you need to make sure that it's actually resourced

00:05:49.540 --> 00:05:50.820
because this is real work.

00:05:50.820 --> 00:05:51.660
This is hard.

00:05:51.660 --> 00:05:53.459
This is not someone's passion project.

00:05:53.459 --> 00:05:56.299
You want to make sure that this is resourced appropriately.

00:05:58.859 --> 00:06:00.700
With that, I can go into the middle,

00:06:00.700 --> 00:06:03.579
which is that data should be protected and compliant.

00:06:03.579 --> 00:06:06.980
So this is thinking a little bit more about data defense.

00:06:08.739 --> 00:06:11.820
We need to make sure that the data is well-protected

00:06:11.980 --> 00:06:13.299
wherever it's used.

00:06:13.299 --> 00:06:16.100
And I think this is to make sure,

00:06:16.100 --> 00:06:19.579
at Biotim we work with highly sensitive data,

00:06:19.579 --> 00:06:21.380
but all data that you're going to be working with

00:06:21.380 --> 00:06:23.779
is going to have some level of sensitivity to it.

00:06:23.779 --> 00:06:24.619
And you just want to make sure

00:06:24.619 --> 00:06:27.859
that these permission controls persist as you use the data

00:06:27.859 --> 00:06:30.100
and perhaps move the data across the org.

00:06:32.260 --> 00:06:34.619
The one under it is about data compliance,

00:06:36.179 --> 00:06:40.899
GDPR, and then other data privacy protection regulations

00:06:40.899 --> 00:06:42.579
have come into play.

00:06:42.579 --> 00:06:43.739
You really need to think about these.

00:06:43.739 --> 00:06:44.940
How can I use this data?

00:06:44.940 --> 00:06:47.100
If this is not familiar to you,

00:06:47.100 --> 00:06:48.339
get familiar with it quickly,

00:06:48.339 --> 00:06:50.459
find the person stewarding the data

00:06:50.459 --> 00:06:52.260
and understand it from them.

00:06:52.260 --> 00:06:57.260
But there are also more contractual data use agreements

00:06:57.260 --> 00:06:58.459
that come into play

00:06:59.820 --> 00:07:03.339
that can really change how data can and cannot be used.

00:07:06.299 --> 00:07:09.660
I love tying that one back to your number one, right?

00:07:09.700 --> 00:07:11.899
Because if you're creating data that's going to be used,

00:07:11.899 --> 00:07:13.260
it's a lot easier to protect

00:07:13.260 --> 00:07:16.540
and make sure you're compliant on smaller volumes of data.

00:07:16.540 --> 00:07:19.459
So if you know exactly what it's being used for

00:07:19.459 --> 00:07:20.459
and why you're using it,

00:07:20.459 --> 00:07:23.299
not just like storing data to store data,

00:07:23.299 --> 00:07:25.619
it's a lot easier to follow these other guidelines

00:07:25.619 --> 00:07:27.899
and make sure that you have protected data,

00:07:27.899 --> 00:07:30.260
especially around like some of the more sensitive data.

00:07:30.260 --> 00:07:33.299
I know you guys do a lot of medical related data.

00:07:33.299 --> 00:07:36.459
We have an insurance, a lot of like private PII data,

00:07:37.380 --> 00:07:39.420
which is personally identifiable information.

00:07:39.420 --> 00:07:41.380
And so we really have to be careful around it.

00:07:41.380 --> 00:07:42.700
And one of the ways to be careful

00:07:42.700 --> 00:07:44.779
is not to store the things you don't need.

00:07:46.299 --> 00:07:47.339
Yeah, that's a great point.

00:07:47.339 --> 00:07:50.459
And I think that leads nicely into the stuff on the right,

00:07:50.459 --> 00:07:52.820
which is the single sorts of truth.

00:07:52.820 --> 00:07:55.140
You know, data should be shared in place

00:07:55.140 --> 00:07:58.140
and trying to be centralized,

00:07:58.140 --> 00:08:00.339
not like you're saying have many copies of it

00:08:00.339 --> 00:08:01.899
all over the place, which is hard to protect

00:08:01.899 --> 00:08:05.899
and adds, you know, overhead onto it.

00:08:06.619 --> 00:08:08.019
I do think single source of truth

00:08:08.019 --> 00:08:10.220
is a little bit of an aspirational goal.

00:08:10.220 --> 00:08:13.339
I think it's kind of our intention of where we're going,

00:08:13.339 --> 00:08:17.059
but there are, you know, there are technical limitations.

00:08:17.059 --> 00:08:19.220
There are departmental limitations

00:08:19.220 --> 00:08:22.540
that require different copies of data to be made.

00:08:22.540 --> 00:08:24.459
And there's just some sort of pragmatism

00:08:24.459 --> 00:08:26.700
that we have to take when we think about this.

00:08:28.619 --> 00:08:30.739
And the last one is to consider producers

00:08:30.739 --> 00:08:32.059
and consumers of data.

00:08:32.059 --> 00:08:34.580
I do think as data users,

00:08:34.580 --> 00:08:36.780
we often think we're at the end of the line,

00:08:36.780 --> 00:08:40.780
like all the data gets generated, cleaned, created,

00:08:40.780 --> 00:08:42.580
and then it comes to us,

00:08:42.580 --> 00:08:44.619
and then we do something and that's it.

00:08:44.619 --> 00:08:46.260
But I think we should make sure that we know

00:08:46.260 --> 00:08:48.940
that we're in the middle of the line.

00:08:48.940 --> 00:08:51.419
So like there's someone who produces something

00:08:51.419 --> 00:08:53.659
that we use, that we consume,

00:08:53.659 --> 00:08:56.940
but we produce something that someone else consumes.

00:08:56.940 --> 00:08:58.500
So I think when you understand this,

00:08:58.500 --> 00:09:00.820
that you're in the middle and not at the end,

00:09:00.820 --> 00:09:03.419
you start thinking about the data that you produce

00:09:03.419 --> 00:09:05.580
and how to make sure that it's used

00:09:05.580 --> 00:09:06.940
by the people downstream from you

00:09:06.940 --> 00:09:08.380
and how are you a better partner

00:09:08.380 --> 00:09:11.059
to what's being done upstream from you.

00:09:12.739 --> 00:09:15.099
Yeah, I love that especially because

00:09:15.099 --> 00:09:17.140
I think people are gonna do what people are gonna do.

00:09:17.140 --> 00:09:20.659
So it's more, you know, more effective

00:09:20.659 --> 00:09:22.700
to meet them where they are sometimes

00:09:22.700 --> 00:09:24.659
and realize that they're actually gonna do these things

00:09:24.659 --> 00:09:26.539
with your data and figure out the best way

00:09:26.539 --> 00:09:29.140
you can manage that and keep aware of it

00:09:29.140 --> 00:09:30.340
rather than just say no,

00:09:30.340 --> 00:09:32.580
and then they go and they do it anyway.

00:09:32.979 --> 00:09:35.419
And in a less effective, less documented way.

00:09:35.419 --> 00:09:37.580
So I also love that kind of idea

00:09:37.580 --> 00:09:39.700
of creating like the clear roles and responsibilities,

00:09:39.700 --> 00:09:42.260
but also creating like a toolkit around like,

00:09:42.260 --> 00:09:43.859
let's make sure this is documented.

00:09:43.859 --> 00:09:46.340
Let's make it easy for you to do this work.

00:09:46.340 --> 00:09:48.179
Let's make it easy for you to tell me what you're doing

00:09:48.179 --> 00:09:50.700
or make sure that I understand exactly

00:09:50.700 --> 00:09:52.820
where this data is going and how you're using it.

00:09:52.820 --> 00:09:56.419
So I can enable you rather than kind of trying to cut it off,

00:09:57.979 --> 00:10:00.820
which has opposite effects frequently.

00:10:00.820 --> 00:10:04.419
Again, I think there's a lot about what's possible

00:10:04.419 --> 00:10:06.700
when you know what's there.

00:10:06.700 --> 00:10:08.739
And if you don't know what's there,

00:10:08.739 --> 00:10:12.580
you like abnormally constrict yourself.

00:10:12.580 --> 00:10:15.020
So just even knowing stuff is there,

00:10:15.020 --> 00:10:17.059
knowing who your consumers are,

00:10:17.059 --> 00:10:18.179
knowing who your producers are,

00:10:18.179 --> 00:10:19.619
having conversations with them,

00:10:19.619 --> 00:10:21.500
starting to learn about what's there,

00:10:21.500 --> 00:10:22.539
what information they have,

00:10:22.539 --> 00:10:24.179
how you can start accessing it.

00:10:24.179 --> 00:10:27.299
I think that starts breeding some innovative thought.

00:10:28.299 --> 00:10:29.140
Awesome.

00:10:29.140 --> 00:10:30.619
Well, thank you both so much.

00:10:30.619 --> 00:10:32.619
I know I mentioned earlier,

00:10:32.619 --> 00:10:34.820
there were so many questions that were submitted

00:10:34.820 --> 00:10:37.179
ahead of time when people RSVP'd.

00:10:37.179 --> 00:10:40.179
So I can kick us off with a few of those there,

00:10:40.179 --> 00:10:41.580
but again, I encourage you all

00:10:41.580 --> 00:10:43.659
to put questions into the chat as well.

00:10:43.659 --> 00:10:47.020
We wanna make this a discussion with the community.

00:10:47.020 --> 00:10:49.659
But one of the first questions was,

00:10:49.659 --> 00:10:51.940
how do you effectively communicate

00:10:51.940 --> 00:10:54.460
data management standards to your team?

00:10:54.460 --> 00:10:56.140
And how do you engage with teams

00:10:56.140 --> 00:10:58.700
that are resistant to change?

00:10:58.700 --> 00:11:01.380
And Jamie, I'd love to have you start off with this one.

00:11:01.380 --> 00:11:02.219
Sure.

00:11:02.219 --> 00:11:03.739
I think the easiest way to do that

00:11:03.739 --> 00:11:07.219
is to make the change as easy as possible for them, right?

00:11:07.219 --> 00:11:08.940
And the way that I like to do that

00:11:08.940 --> 00:11:12.460
is make a toolkit or make a framework, right?

00:11:12.460 --> 00:11:15.219
If you have a really easy tool to document things,

00:11:15.219 --> 00:11:16.179
like giving them that,

00:11:16.179 --> 00:11:18.099
even if it's something as simple as an Excel,

00:11:18.099 --> 00:11:19.940
like kind of meeting them where you are

00:11:19.940 --> 00:11:23.820
versus getting the best possible tool.

00:11:24.260 --> 00:11:26.619
But in a lot of ways, to me,

00:11:26.619 --> 00:11:29.659
the reason people resist change in a lot of circumstances

00:11:29.659 --> 00:11:32.940
seems to not be because they don't want to change

00:11:32.940 --> 00:11:34.539
or they don't see the value.

00:11:34.539 --> 00:11:35.940
It seems to be a lot more around,

00:11:35.940 --> 00:11:37.299
I have a lot of other things to do

00:11:37.299 --> 00:11:39.099
and this is the worst thing on my list

00:11:39.099 --> 00:11:40.179
and it's not gonna help me,

00:11:40.179 --> 00:11:42.020
it's gonna help someone else later.

00:11:42.020 --> 00:11:44.500
So giving them tools that make it really easy

00:11:44.500 --> 00:11:47.780
for them to document or make it really easy for them to share

00:11:47.780 --> 00:11:50.260
or even if it's just having a common storage location

00:11:50.260 --> 00:11:52.419
where you can go find it later

00:11:53.380 --> 00:11:54.219
and deal with it,

00:11:54.219 --> 00:11:56.260
I think really helps along the process.

00:11:56.260 --> 00:11:58.659
And that to me has gotten a lot further

00:11:58.659 --> 00:11:59.940
than trying to really get people

00:11:59.940 --> 00:12:01.580
to rethink the way that they work,

00:12:01.580 --> 00:12:03.179
which is a much longer term,

00:12:03.179 --> 00:12:05.539
harder thing to transition through.

00:12:05.539 --> 00:12:06.780
But you can do it a lot,

00:12:06.780 --> 00:12:08.099
especially when there's new hires,

00:12:08.099 --> 00:12:10.739
kind of teaching them that as you bring them in.

00:12:10.739 --> 00:12:13.179
I'm curious, Dan, kind of with a bigger organization,

00:12:13.179 --> 00:12:14.820
how do you guys think about that?

00:12:15.780 --> 00:12:16.619
Oh, that's great.

00:12:16.619 --> 00:12:19.219
I think you're really hitting on the key points here.

00:12:20.099 --> 00:12:23.179
Often when you see resistance to change,

00:12:23.179 --> 00:12:26.020
people don't know what you're asking them to do.

00:12:26.020 --> 00:12:28.419
So I think the stuff that you're saying is like,

00:12:28.419 --> 00:12:29.460
just do this,

00:12:29.460 --> 00:12:30.500
like you give them something,

00:12:30.500 --> 00:12:32.059
just fill out this form.

00:12:32.059 --> 00:12:35.059
And that is much, much easier than saying,

00:12:35.059 --> 00:12:38.260
be a better data steward, right?

00:12:38.260 --> 00:12:41.500
And that does not evoke change.

00:12:43.539 --> 00:12:45.299
But as I do get further in my career,

00:12:45.299 --> 00:12:46.140
I think about,

00:12:46.140 --> 00:12:47.900
trying to make change in the organization

00:12:47.900 --> 00:12:49.739
to change is very, very hard.

00:12:50.659 --> 00:12:53.219
So let's make sure that when we are making change,

00:12:53.219 --> 00:12:55.940
that there is a value statement behind it.

00:12:55.940 --> 00:12:58.140
And that we keep bringing that back up

00:12:58.140 --> 00:13:01.020
to help people really tie what they're doing

00:13:01.020 --> 00:13:03.619
back to what value they're creating out of it.

00:13:04.820 --> 00:13:06.299
There is this change management framework

00:13:06.299 --> 00:13:07.299
that I really like.

00:13:07.299 --> 00:13:09.260
It's from this book called Switch

00:13:09.260 --> 00:13:13.099
by Chip and Dan Heath in the 1880s.

00:13:13.419 --> 00:13:14.940
By Chip and Dan Heath.

00:13:15.820 --> 00:13:20.820
And they have a nice picture about how change happens,

00:13:20.859 --> 00:13:24.260
which is you have an elephant,

00:13:24.260 --> 00:13:26.380
and then you have someone riding the elephant,

00:13:26.380 --> 00:13:28.140
and then the elephant is on a path.

00:13:29.380 --> 00:13:32.659
So the elephant is the emotional mind.

00:13:32.659 --> 00:13:34.940
This is like how you feel about things.

00:13:34.940 --> 00:13:37.260
And the rider is your rational mind.

00:13:38.179 --> 00:13:41.580
And then the path is how you actually get there.

00:13:41.580 --> 00:13:44.900
So I think what Jamie was talking about is the path.

00:13:44.900 --> 00:13:46.419
You gotta make the path really easy

00:13:46.419 --> 00:13:48.659
for the elephant to plod along on.

00:13:50.179 --> 00:13:51.619
But you have to,

00:13:51.619 --> 00:13:53.179
and you can talk to the rational mind

00:13:53.179 --> 00:13:54.820
and saying, these things are important.

00:13:54.820 --> 00:13:56.460
This is a GDPR requirement.

00:13:56.460 --> 00:13:57.299
You have to do this.

00:13:57.299 --> 00:14:00.140
I'll show you the statistics of why this is more effective.

00:14:00.140 --> 00:14:01.979
But the rider on the elephant,

00:14:01.979 --> 00:14:04.580
he gets tired of pulling the elephant at some point.

00:14:04.580 --> 00:14:06.780
And eventually the elephant just goes down the path.

00:14:06.780 --> 00:14:10.940
So you do have to affect that emotional mind too,

00:14:10.940 --> 00:14:13.340
and then make the path really easy.

00:14:13.340 --> 00:14:16.580
So your best bet is when the elephant just goes

00:14:16.580 --> 00:14:18.739
and the path is just obvious for them.

00:14:19.619 --> 00:14:21.700
But when you're trying to steer the elephant

00:14:21.700 --> 00:14:22.820
into a new direction,

00:14:22.820 --> 00:14:25.219
you have to think about the rational,

00:14:25.219 --> 00:14:26.820
the emotional, and the path,

00:14:26.820 --> 00:14:28.419
and try to move that forward.

00:14:31.260 --> 00:14:34.219
And Dan, I know you just mentioned GDPR there.

00:14:34.219 --> 00:14:36.940
And I remember, Jamie, when we were talking earlier,

00:14:36.940 --> 00:14:39.099
you mentioned people need to recognize

00:14:39.099 --> 00:14:41.059
that it's a problem as well,

00:14:42.140 --> 00:14:45.179
and showing the pain of the actual issue.

00:14:45.179 --> 00:14:48.099
I was wondering if you had any other thoughts on that too.

00:14:50.619 --> 00:14:53.020
I mean, I think one of the biggest data transformations

00:14:53.020 --> 00:14:55.179
I've ever seen came from California's right

00:14:55.179 --> 00:14:57.099
to be forgotten law,

00:14:57.099 --> 00:15:00.260
where companies had to be able to get rid

00:15:00.260 --> 00:15:01.859
of all record of someone.

00:15:01.859 --> 00:15:03.099
You could go and you could request

00:15:03.099 --> 00:15:04.340
to the company in California,

00:15:04.340 --> 00:15:06.619
hey, I don't wanna be in your data anymore.

00:15:06.619 --> 00:15:08.900
And one of the big challenges for companies was

00:15:09.700 --> 00:15:11.299
they actually couldn't connect a record

00:15:11.299 --> 00:15:13.099
across all their different systems.

00:15:13.099 --> 00:15:18.099
And that was a financial and otherwise legal incentive

00:15:18.659 --> 00:15:21.099
where they actually had to make these huge transformations

00:15:21.099 --> 00:15:23.340
of the data systems to make that feasible.

00:15:23.340 --> 00:15:25.140
Now, those transformations

00:15:25.140 --> 00:15:27.140
actually enabled all their systems.

00:15:27.140 --> 00:15:28.739
It enables things like AI.

00:15:28.739 --> 00:15:29.580
If you wanna do that,

00:15:29.580 --> 00:15:32.179
you have to have your systems connected effectively.

00:15:32.179 --> 00:15:34.299
But none of those things are usually incentive enough

00:15:34.299 --> 00:15:36.780
to go through one of those massive transformations.

00:15:36.780 --> 00:15:37.700
They're expensive.

00:15:37.700 --> 00:15:39.140
They're really hard to do.

00:15:39.140 --> 00:15:41.739
The historic data is really hard to mess with.

00:15:41.739 --> 00:15:45.659
And so I think finding some of those legal things

00:15:45.659 --> 00:15:46.940
that are starting to come out now,

00:15:46.940 --> 00:15:48.859
especially around all this governance,

00:15:48.859 --> 00:15:50.900
I know a lot of folks are like, oh no, governance,

00:15:50.900 --> 00:15:52.099
but I'm actually really excited

00:15:52.099 --> 00:15:53.940
about some of the stuff that's coming out

00:15:53.940 --> 00:15:56.900
because I think it's a great way to give an incentive.

00:15:56.900 --> 00:16:00.419
People seem really excited about investing in data science

00:16:00.419 --> 00:16:01.500
or investing in AI,

00:16:01.500 --> 00:16:02.900
but they seem much less excited

00:16:02.900 --> 00:16:04.299
in investing in the core systems

00:16:04.299 --> 00:16:05.739
that actually make that all possible,

00:16:05.739 --> 00:16:08.020
which are much more tedious, much more expensive

00:16:08.020 --> 00:16:10.419
and are what is actually gonna push us forward.

00:16:10.419 --> 00:16:13.380
And so I know Dan has to deal with that every day.

00:16:13.380 --> 00:16:15.580
I'm curious if he thinks about other incentives,

00:16:15.580 --> 00:16:18.659
but for me, those kind of legal types of boundaries

00:16:18.659 --> 00:16:19.460
that they're putting in place

00:16:19.460 --> 00:16:22.380
actually really give us an incentive to fix those systems

00:16:22.380 --> 00:16:23.700
and make it a lot easier

00:16:23.700 --> 00:16:25.340
that we don't have haphazard pipelines

00:16:25.340 --> 00:16:28.020
from here and there and everywhere trying to connect data.

00:16:28.020 --> 00:16:30.619
And that's really how we get a lot of issues

00:16:30.619 --> 00:16:34.580
with definitions or understanding where something came from

00:16:34.580 --> 00:16:36.299
or using something that was created.

00:16:36.299 --> 00:16:38.140
A lot of that secondary data usage

00:16:38.140 --> 00:16:39.739
where you're using it for one purpose,

00:16:39.739 --> 00:16:40.940
it was created for a different one

00:16:40.940 --> 00:16:42.140
and you didn't realize the definition

00:16:42.140 --> 00:16:43.500
was a little bit different.

00:16:45.539 --> 00:16:47.739
Yeah, no, this is great.

00:16:47.739 --> 00:16:51.140
I do think the regulations push us forward

00:16:51.140 --> 00:16:56.140
and there's a lot of complaints for sure

00:16:56.460 --> 00:17:01.460
when these regulations come out that we have to abide to,

00:17:01.820 --> 00:17:04.500
but I do think that they move us forward

00:17:05.219 --> 00:17:06.060
in a good direction.

00:17:06.060 --> 00:17:07.859
And I think they do have that strategic mindset

00:17:07.859 --> 00:17:08.900
in place like you're saying,

00:17:08.900 --> 00:17:12.020
where this actually helped us in the long-term

00:17:12.020 --> 00:17:13.300
because it connected all these systems

00:17:13.300 --> 00:17:16.660
where we never would have been in this place before.

00:17:16.660 --> 00:17:20.459
One of the things in that change management thing

00:17:20.459 --> 00:17:23.260
is you need to solve a problem.

00:17:23.260 --> 00:17:25.780
You need to solve a problem that actually exists

00:17:25.780 --> 00:17:26.699
and you need to solve a problem

00:17:26.699 --> 00:17:29.060
that is recognized to exist.

00:17:29.060 --> 00:17:30.859
So GDPR is a great one.

00:17:30.859 --> 00:17:32.099
Here's this new law.

00:17:32.900 --> 00:17:34.500
Are you compliant to GDPR?

00:17:34.500 --> 00:17:36.140
Have we ever heard of GDPR before?

00:17:36.140 --> 00:17:36.979
No.

00:17:36.979 --> 00:17:41.060
So it's a clear problem to be able to go implement it.

00:17:41.060 --> 00:17:43.859
And I think as you look across

00:17:43.859 --> 00:17:46.060
all different problems like this,

00:17:46.060 --> 00:17:49.060
the more you can bring visibility to the issue,

00:17:49.060 --> 00:17:51.459
you could start to feel the pain a little,

00:17:51.459 --> 00:17:54.459
show the pain to the organization.

00:17:54.459 --> 00:17:56.380
That's where you start to get people

00:17:56.380 --> 00:17:58.660
to adjust their mindset and say,

00:17:58.660 --> 00:18:00.459
this is a problem, I see this as a problem.

00:18:00.459 --> 00:18:01.339
We need to change this.

00:18:01.339 --> 00:18:02.660
We need to change this.

00:18:02.660 --> 00:18:06.219
And you can start moving the organization forward like that.

00:18:07.739 --> 00:18:10.739
We had a bit of an issue with the recording,

00:18:10.739 --> 00:18:11.939
the first go around.

00:18:11.939 --> 00:18:14.699
So you'll notice that for the first part here,

00:18:14.699 --> 00:18:16.739
all of a sudden we have different lighting,

00:18:16.739 --> 00:18:19.939
different shirts or different hairstyles.

00:18:19.939 --> 00:18:22.660
So if you're wondering why, that's why.

00:18:22.660 --> 00:18:26.260
I see there was a question that came into the chat

00:18:26.260 --> 00:18:27.099
a little bit.

00:18:27.099 --> 00:18:27.939
Oh, and real quickly,

00:18:28.500 --> 00:18:30.660
a reference to that book again.

00:18:30.660 --> 00:18:31.500
What was it?

00:18:31.500 --> 00:18:32.900
I'm sure it was called Switch.

00:18:32.900 --> 00:18:34.500
Hey Chris, I'll put it in there.

00:18:36.939 --> 00:18:39.819
I see Timothy, you had a question in the chat

00:18:39.819 --> 00:18:40.660
a little bit earlier.

00:18:40.660 --> 00:18:42.380
Do you want to jump in here,

00:18:42.380 --> 00:18:43.979
introduce yourself and ask that?

00:18:49.140 --> 00:18:50.540
Hey everybody, thanks a lot.

00:18:51.420 --> 00:18:52.260
I'm Tim York.

00:18:52.260 --> 00:18:56.339
I'm at Virginia Commonwealth University, a professor there.

00:18:56.339 --> 00:18:58.900
I was wondering, we run into this problem a lot.

00:18:58.900 --> 00:19:00.699
We store a lot of data.

00:19:00.699 --> 00:19:02.260
Are there guidelines standards

00:19:02.260 --> 00:19:04.780
for the minimally reported information

00:19:04.780 --> 00:19:07.420
that must accompany a data set?

00:19:07.420 --> 00:19:10.459
Are there accepted standards out there that are published?

00:19:14.459 --> 00:19:15.500
I don't know of one.

00:19:15.500 --> 00:19:17.739
That would be amazing, right?

00:19:17.739 --> 00:19:18.579
No.

00:19:20.339 --> 00:19:23.739
I think we're all trying to figure out what good is, right?

00:19:24.619 --> 00:19:28.500
What's the minimum good that we should just abide by?

00:19:28.500 --> 00:19:32.339
I'd kind of ask that back to everyone on the call here.

00:19:33.260 --> 00:19:36.060
Is there something, some set of metadata,

00:19:37.020 --> 00:19:40.060
some set of general standards around it?

00:19:40.060 --> 00:19:42.579
I would say maybe just quickly,

00:19:42.579 --> 00:19:44.459
since you mentioned you're at a university,

00:19:44.459 --> 00:19:48.219
what your IRB has, that's a really good place.

00:19:48.219 --> 00:19:50.420
So the Internal Review Board for Research.

00:19:50.420 --> 00:19:53.020
So those are for folks not used to university systems,

00:19:53.020 --> 00:19:54.540
the folks that approve research.

00:19:54.540 --> 00:19:56.579
They also typically have some data guidelines

00:19:56.579 --> 00:19:57.699
around what you're allowed to store,

00:19:57.699 --> 00:19:59.300
how you're allowed to store it, things like that.

00:19:59.300 --> 00:20:00.900
So that's a good place to start.

00:20:02.020 --> 00:20:03.859
In insurance, we have really strict regs.

00:20:03.859 --> 00:20:06.819
So by industry, like what we're allowed to store

00:20:06.819 --> 00:20:08.579
about people, how long we're allowed to use it,

00:20:08.579 --> 00:20:10.180
things like that.

00:20:10.180 --> 00:20:11.020
I'm curious.

00:20:11.020 --> 00:20:14.099
So yeah, like what Dan said, if anyone else on the,

00:20:14.099 --> 00:20:15.099
I don't see anyone in the chat

00:20:15.099 --> 00:20:16.699
that's jumping for joy on this one,

00:20:16.699 --> 00:20:21.060
but any other folks that have experience

00:20:21.060 --> 00:20:22.420
with some standards?

00:20:24.020 --> 00:20:25.979
And also if you want to jump in,

00:20:25.979 --> 00:20:28.219
you can raise your hand on Zoom.

00:20:28.219 --> 00:20:31.060
So if you see the reactions bar below,

00:20:31.060 --> 00:20:35.619
if you click that, it will let you raise your hand too.

00:20:38.939 --> 00:20:43.380
So in academics, we typically try to store a codebook

00:20:43.380 --> 00:20:47.099
along with the data and also meet all of our IRB regulations

00:20:47.099 --> 00:20:50.939
in terms of security on where to store the data.

00:20:51.459 --> 00:20:53.540
But outside of that, I was just curious

00:20:53.540 --> 00:20:58.540
if there's any other kind of information per datasets

00:20:58.819 --> 00:21:02.420
that you guys always associate with the data.

00:21:04.939 --> 00:21:05.780
Yeah.

00:21:05.780 --> 00:21:08.660
Like I think you're saying like a data dictionary

00:21:08.660 --> 00:21:11.699
or a codebook is probably what you're calling it.

00:21:11.699 --> 00:21:12.540
Yeah.

00:21:12.540 --> 00:21:14.060
I mean, I think a couple of things.

00:21:14.060 --> 00:21:14.900
Like who's the owner?

00:21:14.900 --> 00:21:16.300
Who's the, who should it be directed?

00:21:16.300 --> 00:21:17.140
Who has permission?

00:21:17.140 --> 00:21:19.900
Like you were talking about, who has ownership of the data?

00:21:19.900 --> 00:21:22.540
Who has permissions to do X, Y, and Z?

00:21:22.540 --> 00:21:25.579
Who is ultimately responsible for the data?

00:21:25.579 --> 00:21:28.660
I guess those types of sort of metadata

00:21:28.660 --> 00:21:30.739
that should always travel with the data.

00:21:32.579 --> 00:21:33.420
Yeah.

00:21:33.420 --> 00:21:35.979
I think there's actually reasonably good research

00:21:35.979 --> 00:21:38.459
out on those sorts of high level topics.

00:21:38.459 --> 00:21:42.939
And so, and a few of the different like data framework

00:21:44.739 --> 00:21:46.300
that exist have those.

00:21:46.300 --> 00:21:48.819
A lot of times we like to think about kind of like,

00:21:48.819 --> 00:21:51.300
I think for a while there were like the five Vs of the data

00:21:51.300 --> 00:21:53.900
but like that's kind of moved on.

00:21:53.900 --> 00:21:56.380
But I like to think about like, where did it come from?

00:21:56.380 --> 00:21:58.219
What was its intended use?

00:21:58.219 --> 00:22:01.180
So is it primary or secondary initially?

00:22:01.180 --> 00:22:04.020
And then who created it at what time did they create it?

00:22:04.020 --> 00:22:07.420
What time scale does it go over is a really big one

00:22:07.420 --> 00:22:09.819
because a lot of times you can kind of think

00:22:09.819 --> 00:22:12.339
about how things will be changing over time.

00:22:12.339 --> 00:22:15.300
And I think I'd have to pull up a resource.

00:22:15.300 --> 00:22:16.140
There's a couple of resources.

00:22:16.140 --> 00:22:18.739
I can put one as a follow-up.

00:22:19.540 --> 00:22:20.900
They do have like broad guidelines

00:22:20.900 --> 00:22:22.339
for what sort of information

00:22:22.339 --> 00:22:24.579
at that high level you should be keeping.

00:22:24.579 --> 00:22:27.300
But really time, location,

00:22:27.300 --> 00:22:28.939
and any sort of like discrepancies

00:22:28.939 --> 00:22:32.459
or known potential issues.

00:22:32.459 --> 00:22:34.660
And then the reason you source it is the biggest one

00:22:34.660 --> 00:22:37.219
because like going back to Dan's slide,

00:22:37.219 --> 00:22:38.420
I think it's really interesting to say

00:22:38.420 --> 00:22:39.699
we have a single source of the truth

00:22:39.699 --> 00:22:41.180
because at a lot of companies,

00:22:41.180 --> 00:22:44.939
different departments will consider a different calculation,

00:22:44.939 --> 00:22:46.459
the same source of the truth.

00:22:46.459 --> 00:22:49.260
So if you think about like finance and actuarial,

00:22:49.260 --> 00:22:50.579
or maybe even within finance,

00:22:50.579 --> 00:22:51.900
they'll have a few different definitions

00:22:51.900 --> 00:22:53.739
of the same term sometimes.

00:22:53.739 --> 00:22:54.699
And so if you don't know why

00:22:54.699 --> 00:22:56.180
that data was being used originally,

00:22:56.180 --> 00:22:59.339
you don't know which definition it's going to be.

00:22:59.339 --> 00:23:01.300
And I presume that's for your type of research as well

00:23:01.300 --> 00:23:04.260
if another professor wants to go pick it up.

00:23:04.260 --> 00:23:05.540
Yeah, thank you.

00:23:05.540 --> 00:23:06.699
Yeah, I think you could.

00:23:06.699 --> 00:23:08.780
Only one I would add to Jamie's list there

00:23:08.780 --> 00:23:10.099
is who can use it.

00:23:11.540 --> 00:23:15.219
You know, I think sometimes we have data

00:23:15.219 --> 00:23:16.339
where anyone can use it.

00:23:17.219 --> 00:23:18.060
Sometimes we have data

00:23:18.060 --> 00:23:20.260
that has a very limited data use agreement.

00:23:20.260 --> 00:23:21.579
And so we need to restrict it.

00:23:21.579 --> 00:23:24.180
And so a little bit of that knowledge upfront,

00:23:24.180 --> 00:23:25.300
we were just talking about this,

00:23:25.300 --> 00:23:27.819
like having some sort of data list that has like,

00:23:27.819 --> 00:23:29.979
you know, what the data set is,

00:23:29.979 --> 00:23:31.260
who to contact about it,

00:23:31.260 --> 00:23:33.060
what the data set means,

00:23:33.979 --> 00:23:36.859
and where it is and who can use it

00:23:36.859 --> 00:23:39.099
is a pretty good first pass.

00:23:39.099 --> 00:23:40.459
And then I think you want to get into like

00:23:40.459 --> 00:23:42.020
what you were talking about there.

00:23:42.020 --> 00:23:44.739
It's like, what did the individual columns

00:23:44.739 --> 00:23:45.579
in the data set mean?

00:23:45.579 --> 00:23:47.420
What did the individual values mean?

00:23:47.420 --> 00:23:48.900
What, how can you add, you know,

00:23:48.900 --> 00:23:50.739
and then you can kind of just snowball from there

00:23:50.739 --> 00:23:53.140
of like how far you want to go.

00:23:55.300 --> 00:23:56.500
Matthew, I see your hands raised.

00:23:56.500 --> 00:23:57.579
Want to jump in here?

00:23:58.540 --> 00:24:01.900
Yeah, so just to do a quick intro,

00:24:01.900 --> 00:24:04.099
I head Enterprise Data and AI Services.

00:24:04.099 --> 00:24:05.459
I report to the CTO.

00:24:05.459 --> 00:24:06.380
I'm an IT side,

00:24:06.380 --> 00:24:09.619
so responsible for anything about data and AI

00:24:09.619 --> 00:24:11.979
within a global organization.

00:24:11.979 --> 00:24:13.180
I'm in insurance.

00:24:13.180 --> 00:24:16.219
And so I think that,

00:24:16.219 --> 00:24:18.260
which probably one of my favorite answers right now

00:24:18.260 --> 00:24:20.099
is that, well, it depends because,

00:24:20.099 --> 00:24:23.380
so it really has a depending on where you are.

00:24:23.380 --> 00:24:24.500
Are you a global company?

00:24:24.500 --> 00:24:25.459
Are you a regional company?

00:24:25.459 --> 00:24:27.660
Are you someone who's in the Pacific state

00:24:27.660 --> 00:24:29.579
to have certain laws or whatnot?

00:24:29.579 --> 00:24:32.020
Also, what industry you're in.

00:24:32.020 --> 00:24:33.099
In pharmaceuticals,

00:24:33.099 --> 00:24:34.660
I used to work for a pharmaceutical as well,

00:24:34.660 --> 00:24:36.140
and we had a lot more rules

00:24:36.140 --> 00:24:38.619
on what it needs to use to define a data set

00:24:38.660 --> 00:24:43.579
versus when I was at a college.

00:24:43.579 --> 00:24:46.339
So it very depends on where you are.

00:24:46.339 --> 00:24:47.699
So that's why you won't really find

00:24:47.699 --> 00:24:49.540
a general set of requirements,

00:24:49.540 --> 00:24:50.900
but rather suggestions.

00:24:50.900 --> 00:24:51.859
And as you see here,

00:24:51.859 --> 00:24:54.140
everyone commenting that here are the things

00:24:54.140 --> 00:24:54.979
you'll look at and whatnot,

00:24:54.979 --> 00:24:56.260
but a lot of this all comes

00:24:56.260 --> 00:24:58.180
from a data governance practice.

00:24:58.180 --> 00:24:59.859
So ideally there should be,

00:24:59.859 --> 00:25:02.420
and I say ideally because I don't think it happens

00:25:02.420 --> 00:25:05.859
everywhere, but there should be a data governance

00:25:05.859 --> 00:25:08.140
group of folks within a organization

00:25:08.140 --> 00:25:10.300
and community set of people

00:25:10.300 --> 00:25:12.540
that help define what this is.

00:25:12.540 --> 00:25:14.020
And that is gonna be definition

00:25:14.020 --> 00:25:16.020
that you're gonna be using going forward.

00:25:16.020 --> 00:25:19.900
So I know some folks mentioned that in universities,

00:25:19.900 --> 00:25:21.260
there is a document out there

00:25:21.260 --> 00:25:22.619
that kind of defines what that is.

00:25:22.619 --> 00:25:24.380
And so that my assumption is that

00:25:24.380 --> 00:25:26.500
there is some type of data governance people

00:25:26.500 --> 00:25:28.540
together defining that.

00:25:28.540 --> 00:25:32.500
But in reality, it really depends on who you are,

00:25:32.500 --> 00:25:36.739
where you are, and a large organization.

00:25:36.739 --> 00:25:38.859
So unfortunately that's one of those answers

00:25:38.859 --> 00:25:41.699
that I get once in a while that it does depend.

00:25:44.619 --> 00:25:46.219
Thank you.

00:25:46.219 --> 00:25:48.859
I'll jump over to the next question here.

00:25:48.859 --> 00:25:50.819
And I get the feeling that we could have

00:25:50.819 --> 00:25:53.500
an all day conference on this topic,

00:25:53.500 --> 00:25:56.020
considering we just did one question there.

00:25:56.020 --> 00:25:58.140
But the other one was,

00:25:58.140 --> 00:25:59.819
what do you think of the idea

00:25:59.819 --> 00:26:02.420
that data governance should be rebranded

00:26:02.420 --> 00:26:03.939
as data enablement?

00:26:07.339 --> 00:26:08.819
I have strong views here.

00:26:10.140 --> 00:26:11.819
Do you want me to go first, Jamie?

00:26:14.099 --> 00:26:16.540
So my strong view here is that

00:26:16.540 --> 00:26:18.660
there's no one on this call who thinks,

00:26:18.660 --> 00:26:20.180
who likes data governance.

00:26:21.339 --> 00:26:23.099
Even I think when you talk to the people

00:26:23.099 --> 00:26:24.739
who do data governance professionally,

00:26:24.739 --> 00:26:26.219
they're like, yeah, but you know,

00:26:26.219 --> 00:26:27.619
it's not really,

00:26:27.619 --> 00:26:29.739
like they try to talk themselves out of it.

00:26:29.739 --> 00:26:32.060
There's something with the word governance

00:26:32.060 --> 00:26:35.140
that just holds a lot of baggage for people.

00:26:35.140 --> 00:26:36.619
Oh, you're gonna tell me how to do my work?

00:26:37.500 --> 00:26:38.339
I'm the analyst.

00:26:38.339 --> 00:26:39.380
I'm the data scientist here.

00:26:39.380 --> 00:26:42.300
You're gonna tell me what I can do without my data?

00:26:43.180 --> 00:26:48.180
So I saw that really early in this journey,

00:26:48.420 --> 00:26:51.939
and I immediately rebranded it to data stewardship

00:26:53.099 --> 00:26:57.380
because of this baggage that's there.

00:26:57.380 --> 00:27:02.380
And I think what's happening on our data ecosystems

00:27:02.500 --> 00:27:05.500
is that we used to be all centralized, right?

00:27:05.500 --> 00:27:08.300
There's like centralized, centralized, centralized.

00:27:08.300 --> 00:27:09.900
And then you could reasonably

00:27:09.900 --> 00:27:12.579
have a centralized data governance over it.

00:27:13.619 --> 00:27:16.380
But what happens over time is it all spreads out, right?

00:27:16.380 --> 00:27:19.140
And now we're managing the mesh, right?

00:27:19.140 --> 00:27:20.660
And when you manage the mesh,

00:27:20.660 --> 00:27:25.660
you need people at the individual points of it to manage it.

00:27:26.979 --> 00:27:28.380
And so I think that's where you get

00:27:28.380 --> 00:27:31.060
more of a view of a data stewardship.

00:27:31.060 --> 00:27:35.060
You're kind of accountable for your little node of the mesh.

00:27:35.780 --> 00:27:36.979
So if we were to go that further

00:27:36.979 --> 00:27:39.420
and call it data enablement,

00:27:40.540 --> 00:27:45.540
I guess my point here is we're on that journey for sure.

00:27:45.819 --> 00:27:50.819
And data enablement to me is a little too soft of a term,

00:27:51.660 --> 00:27:52.859
but I think it can be something

00:27:52.859 --> 00:27:55.780
that is like pointing us towards we are generating value.

00:27:55.780 --> 00:27:56.780
I think that's what it's trying to say.

00:27:56.780 --> 00:27:58.859
We are generating value through this work.

00:27:58.859 --> 00:28:02.579
This is not busy work just to overly restrict you.

00:28:06.219 --> 00:28:07.219
Yeah, I would agree.

00:28:07.219 --> 00:28:09.260
And I think it depends on who I'm talking to.

00:28:09.260 --> 00:28:10.500
So for senior leadership,

00:28:10.500 --> 00:28:12.300
I think the idea of data governance

00:28:12.300 --> 00:28:14.699
is really just it's expensive, it gets in the way.

00:28:14.699 --> 00:28:16.540
And so data enablement to me

00:28:16.540 --> 00:28:19.099
is a great little advertising catchphrase

00:28:20.420 --> 00:28:22.140
to get us where we need to go

00:28:22.140 --> 00:28:23.979
and what we need investment wise.

00:28:25.660 --> 00:28:27.099
But also I do think it's important

00:28:27.099 --> 00:28:30.180
to have really frank governance conversations

00:28:30.180 --> 00:28:33.260
with data scientists, data engineers, et cetera,

00:28:33.260 --> 00:28:35.540
and use that terminology to be really frank

00:28:35.540 --> 00:28:37.739
about the fact that this is something that's important

00:28:37.739 --> 00:28:39.140
that we have to care about.

00:28:39.140 --> 00:28:40.979
And this is something that is critical

00:28:40.979 --> 00:28:42.219
to the work that you do.

00:28:43.540 --> 00:28:46.540
And so to me, the branding is more how we fund it,

00:28:46.540 --> 00:28:47.939
how we enable it.

00:28:47.939 --> 00:28:50.380
And the actual terminology is,

00:28:50.380 --> 00:28:53.660
I think sometimes we don't wanna be like Dan said, soft

00:28:53.660 --> 00:28:57.300
when we get down to actually brass tacks of fixing the data

00:28:57.300 --> 00:28:59.420
and cleaning the data and understanding the data.

00:28:59.420 --> 00:29:02.260
And I think a lot of that I feel like can tie back

00:29:02.300 --> 00:29:05.219
to what makes a good data engineer, data scientist,

00:29:05.219 --> 00:29:08.060
which is curiosity in my opinion.

00:29:09.219 --> 00:29:11.300
And so if you're curious about your data,

00:29:11.300 --> 00:29:13.979
you're actually going to be doing data governance

00:29:13.979 --> 00:29:15.099
as you go through it, right?

00:29:15.099 --> 00:29:17.339
You're gonna be asking questions about what looks weird,

00:29:17.339 --> 00:29:18.459
how is this defined?

00:29:18.459 --> 00:29:19.939
Do I understand this?

00:29:19.939 --> 00:29:23.020
And so you being really good at the governance piece

00:29:23.020 --> 00:29:27.140
is you being really good at your piece of the work as well.

00:29:28.140 --> 00:29:28.979
Thank you.

00:29:29.819 --> 00:29:32.540
Another question that was asked ahead of time was,

00:29:32.540 --> 00:29:35.819
it's easy in theory that the organization

00:29:35.819 --> 00:29:38.939
should have a single source of truth of data,

00:29:38.939 --> 00:29:42.300
but in reality, each org has their own definition

00:29:42.300 --> 00:29:45.140
of measures and metrics and what to track

00:29:45.140 --> 00:29:46.459
under the same name.

00:29:46.459 --> 00:29:47.939
How do we overcome that?

00:29:49.939 --> 00:29:52.819
And I'll copy the question over into the chat too.

00:29:52.939 --> 00:29:54.939
I went first the last two times, Jamie.

00:29:55.859 --> 00:29:56.699
Sure.

00:29:56.699 --> 00:29:59.140
So I think this is actually something

00:29:59.140 --> 00:30:00.459
that we should embrace a little more.

00:30:00.459 --> 00:30:01.300
And I don't know, Dan,

00:30:01.300 --> 00:30:04.420
if you're gonna knock my lights out for saying that,

00:30:04.420 --> 00:30:07.339
but it is really important that different definitions

00:30:07.339 --> 00:30:08.739
exist in different environments.

00:30:08.739 --> 00:30:10.939
The question is, how do we tie it all together?

00:30:10.939 --> 00:30:13.099
And so I think that organizations where they say,

00:30:13.099 --> 00:30:14.420
you can only get data from here

00:30:14.420 --> 00:30:16.099
and you can only get it in this way,

00:30:16.099 --> 00:30:18.140
end up with a lot of shadow IT stuff.

00:30:18.140 --> 00:30:20.260
And so I think that's a really good question

00:30:20.260 --> 00:30:21.459
to get it in this way,

00:30:21.459 --> 00:30:23.500
end up with a lot of shadow IT departments

00:30:23.500 --> 00:30:25.660
or shadow servers or shadow data,

00:30:25.660 --> 00:30:27.300
data that's been downloaded and massaged.

00:30:27.300 --> 00:30:28.140
If instead we say,

00:30:28.140 --> 00:30:29.900
we know we have different definitions for this,

00:30:29.900 --> 00:30:32.260
how do we integrate this into our systems?

00:30:32.260 --> 00:30:34.060
That ends up with a much better outcome

00:30:34.060 --> 00:30:35.859
where people actually get what they need,

00:30:35.859 --> 00:30:37.500
which goes back to that first point

00:30:37.500 --> 00:30:39.459
that Dan had on his first slide.

00:30:39.459 --> 00:30:41.739
Like, why are we creating this resource to begin with?

00:30:41.739 --> 00:30:44.619
And I think sometimes in the act of governing

00:30:44.619 --> 00:30:46.939
and setting things up and doing all this work,

00:30:46.939 --> 00:30:49.459
we forget why we started pulling the data together

00:30:49.459 --> 00:30:50.380
in the first place,

00:30:50.380 --> 00:30:52.900
which is usability and functionality.

00:30:52.900 --> 00:30:55.819
And so in this, I would encourage that

00:30:55.819 --> 00:30:59.140
and I would encourage them to write the definition down

00:30:59.140 --> 00:31:01.099
and then we start having our governance, right?

00:31:01.099 --> 00:31:02.819
So you want data a certain way?

00:31:02.819 --> 00:31:03.979
Yeah, let's do it.

00:31:03.979 --> 00:31:04.979
Let's write it down.

00:31:04.979 --> 00:31:06.180
Let's get it framed.

00:31:06.180 --> 00:31:08.260
Let's make sure we have really clear documentation

00:31:08.260 --> 00:31:09.420
and definitions.

00:31:09.420 --> 00:31:11.459
And then let's move forward with your department

00:31:11.459 --> 00:31:13.500
has a slightly different definition than this department

00:31:13.500 --> 00:31:14.339
and that's okay.

00:31:14.339 --> 00:31:18.339
It's in a different layer or it's in a different view

00:31:18.339 --> 00:31:19.859
or whatever, however you want to set it up.

00:31:19.859 --> 00:31:22.780
So I actually really think this is a good thing

00:31:23.619 --> 00:31:25.459
and something that should be encouraged

00:31:25.459 --> 00:31:27.739
because it is the reality of the way we work.

00:31:29.979 --> 00:31:31.939
How can you disagree with that, Jamie?

00:31:32.859 --> 00:31:36.900
Well, I think Jamie said it really well,

00:31:36.900 --> 00:31:39.300
but there's just some reality here.

00:31:39.300 --> 00:31:41.060
People are going to go do their jobs

00:31:41.060 --> 00:31:43.140
whether you like it or not.

00:31:44.099 --> 00:31:49.099
And so when those, but I guess I'm a big proponent

00:31:50.780 --> 00:31:53.099
not to create a process where the only way

00:31:53.099 --> 00:31:56.420
to get your job done is to break the process, right?

00:31:56.420 --> 00:32:00.180
So you need to kind of live in reality here of,

00:32:00.180 --> 00:32:01.939
okay, so we're going to create these different things.

00:32:01.939 --> 00:32:04.060
These different things are going to exist.

00:32:04.060 --> 00:32:06.579
How do we just know that they all exist?

00:32:06.579 --> 00:32:08.339
How do we protect them all?

00:32:08.339 --> 00:32:09.459
There is a little bit of overhead

00:32:09.459 --> 00:32:11.579
every time you do create something.

00:32:11.780 --> 00:32:14.459
So, and there's also a little bit of risk

00:32:14.459 --> 00:32:17.459
if we have two things that look the same

00:32:17.459 --> 00:32:19.780
but they're a little bit different,

00:32:19.780 --> 00:32:22.579
and people think that they're the same.

00:32:22.579 --> 00:32:25.380
That's where we could get into some kind of trickier

00:32:25.380 --> 00:32:27.540
situations that are hard to deal with.

00:32:29.339 --> 00:32:31.699
I'm thinking back, this is a while now,

00:32:31.699 --> 00:32:35.500
but I did some work about looking at Semantic Web

00:32:35.500 --> 00:32:38.380
and they have this idea of collaboration

00:32:38.380 --> 00:32:40.060
without coordination.

00:32:40.060 --> 00:32:42.500
So there's a way to collaborate

00:32:42.500 --> 00:32:45.060
and kind of use the same data,

00:32:45.060 --> 00:32:49.180
but kind of at a meta level, connect it all together.

00:32:49.180 --> 00:32:51.579
And I think that's a really nice way to think about it

00:32:51.579 --> 00:32:54.099
because people will kind of be pulling the data out

00:32:54.099 --> 00:32:57.260
into their individual nodes, into their individual pockets,

00:32:57.260 --> 00:33:01.339
but can we, at this higher meta or semantic level,

00:33:02.219 --> 00:33:03.819
connect that data together

00:33:03.819 --> 00:33:06.380
so that we can manage it a little bit better?

00:33:06.380 --> 00:33:09.020
But that's my thoughts there.

00:33:11.060 --> 00:33:14.780
Matthew, I see you had some thoughts on the thread there

00:33:14.780 --> 00:33:17.260
in the chat, do you want to add anything to that?

00:33:18.660 --> 00:33:22.739
Yeah, so when I started at this organization,

00:33:24.660 --> 00:33:28.660
we just moved off of the prem world.

00:33:28.660 --> 00:33:31.339
And so I mean, moving on to cloud services.

00:33:31.339 --> 00:33:35.420
And so there was no defined enterprise data architecture.

00:33:35.420 --> 00:33:38.140
There was, it was just a glop of different applications

00:33:38.140 --> 00:33:42.459
and they had some integration pipelines to connect them.

00:33:42.459 --> 00:33:46.619
And so the way that we moved forward was coming up,

00:33:46.619 --> 00:33:49.060
well, of course, with ethics of leadership

00:33:50.939 --> 00:33:53.979
and support from the engineers,

00:33:53.979 --> 00:33:57.579
we came up with a defined enterprise data architecture

00:33:57.579 --> 00:33:59.579
and a strategy on how to get there.

00:33:59.579 --> 00:34:04.579
And you build that roadmap and include everyone into that

00:34:05.380 --> 00:34:06.780
to get the alignment to that.

00:34:06.819 --> 00:34:08.620
That's how you move towards to something like that.

00:34:08.620 --> 00:34:11.260
So the one I mentioned here was a medallion architecture.

00:34:11.260 --> 00:34:14.219
So we do use it in our books and daily.

00:34:14.219 --> 00:34:18.459
And so we show how does it work from a general perspective,

00:34:18.459 --> 00:34:21.020
meaning that if I have external or data

00:34:21.020 --> 00:34:22.620
I want to bring in from applications,

00:34:22.620 --> 00:34:23.699
well, you have a raw layer.

00:34:23.699 --> 00:34:25.379
That's where everything comes in.

00:34:25.379 --> 00:34:28.300
No one minute plays, no one does anything to it.

00:34:28.300 --> 00:34:32.139
Then you mature it and bring it to a common data model.

00:34:32.139 --> 00:34:33.939
So again, I think you mentioned earlier

00:34:33.939 --> 00:34:38.939
that every data should have a purpose or a reason to use it.

00:34:40.500 --> 00:34:43.820
And so the reason for us in this common data model

00:34:43.820 --> 00:34:46.500
is to provide the business with a data set

00:34:46.500 --> 00:34:49.699
that has generally all use cases available to it

00:34:49.699 --> 00:34:51.260
because it's the common data model,

00:34:51.260 --> 00:34:53.100
not anything for specific use,

00:34:53.100 --> 00:34:56.340
but specific to commonality that's out there.

00:34:56.340 --> 00:35:00.139
Then you build separate data sets coming from that

00:35:00.260 --> 00:35:03.979
to be the ones that are specific for a given report

00:35:03.979 --> 00:35:06.500
or for given analytics purposes or what that.

00:35:06.500 --> 00:35:08.780
So then you can track down the lineage

00:35:08.780 --> 00:35:11.860
to the source of truth, which is our raw layer.

00:35:12.780 --> 00:35:16.419
So if someone's able to articulate that

00:35:16.419 --> 00:35:18.419
and be able to explain this at many different levels,

00:35:18.419 --> 00:35:22.540
then you can get this body of people who kind of support it

00:35:22.540 --> 00:35:24.500
and want to go in that direction.

00:35:24.500 --> 00:35:27.699
And so that's where now we are actually in this journey,

00:35:27.739 --> 00:35:30.699
moving everything to this enterprise data architecture.

00:35:31.860 --> 00:35:34.340
But again, there's a lot of effort to do that,

00:35:35.300 --> 00:35:39.100
but that's one coming out with that document

00:35:39.100 --> 00:35:41.620
is going to be one of the biggest achievements.

00:35:42.739 --> 00:35:46.179
Yeah, I mean, to me, that's kind of showing the path

00:35:46.179 --> 00:35:47.340
on the change management.

00:35:47.340 --> 00:35:48.979
If you can say like,

00:35:50.020 --> 00:35:50.979
because right now people are probably

00:35:50.979 --> 00:35:53.260
just landing their data wherever

00:35:53.260 --> 00:35:54.899
and then doing something with it.

00:35:55.979 --> 00:35:56.820
But if you could say, look,

00:35:56.820 --> 00:35:58.580
I landed here and then all this stuff

00:35:58.580 --> 00:36:00.100
automatically happens to it.

00:36:00.100 --> 00:36:02.820
All this stuff automatically propagates into silver,

00:36:02.820 --> 00:36:04.780
into gold, it makes it there.

00:36:04.780 --> 00:36:06.379
Like that change management,

00:36:06.379 --> 00:36:09.100
I think it'll always be a little bit

00:36:09.100 --> 00:36:10.979
because you're taking the control away

00:36:10.979 --> 00:36:12.820
from the people on the ground.

00:36:12.820 --> 00:36:15.620
There's always going to be a little rub there.

00:36:15.620 --> 00:36:18.939
But I think if you can really show that pathway,

00:36:18.939 --> 00:36:20.419
this is the easy way to go.

00:36:20.419 --> 00:36:22.179
This is the way the organization is going.

00:36:22.179 --> 00:36:24.379
So just drop your data over here.

00:36:24.379 --> 00:36:26.020
I think that's a great way to go.

00:36:27.820 --> 00:36:30.179
I think this question is really related

00:36:30.179 --> 00:36:32.419
to the one that we just discussed,

00:36:32.419 --> 00:36:35.219
but what is your advice on how to reduce

00:36:35.219 --> 00:36:38.020
duplicate data stewardship?

00:36:38.020 --> 00:36:41.500
Maybe when it's not already at this org-wide level,

00:36:42.659 --> 00:36:44.419
when multiple people are consistently

00:36:44.419 --> 00:36:47.580
making similar data transformations for similar work?

00:36:50.739 --> 00:36:52.500
I would first ask why.

00:36:53.419 --> 00:36:54.820
To me, that's always the first question

00:36:54.820 --> 00:36:57.860
is when you see something like that, why is it happening?

00:36:57.860 --> 00:37:00.500
And if it's actually duplicative,

00:37:00.500 --> 00:37:02.580
I think that's actually more of an HR problem

00:37:02.580 --> 00:37:05.139
you're going to have to deal with, right?

00:37:05.139 --> 00:37:07.179
Do these two roles still need to exist?

00:37:07.179 --> 00:37:10.500
And are these legacy processes that are just happening

00:37:10.500 --> 00:37:12.179
because somebody needed them at one point

00:37:12.179 --> 00:37:14.340
and you can't combine them across?

00:37:14.340 --> 00:37:16.260
So to me, sometimes it's not a data problem,

00:37:16.260 --> 00:37:18.939
it's a organizational structure problem.

00:37:18.939 --> 00:37:21.500
And we see that a lot when companies are,

00:37:21.500 --> 00:37:23.699
especially like insurers, we see that a lot.

00:37:23.699 --> 00:37:24.939
We buy books of business

00:37:24.939 --> 00:37:27.179
and we absorb different pieces of companies.

00:37:27.179 --> 00:37:28.899
And so you'll see, you'll realize suddenly,

00:37:28.899 --> 00:37:31.379
oh, this person pulls the same report as this person.

00:37:31.379 --> 00:37:33.860
So like, do they both need to pull that report

00:37:33.860 --> 00:37:35.979
is my first question before I even try to do it

00:37:35.979 --> 00:37:38.699
as a data focus question.

00:37:38.699 --> 00:37:40.939
If the reason is, well, I define this

00:37:40.939 --> 00:37:43.020
a little bit differently than they define this,

00:37:43.020 --> 00:37:45.179
then that's a great time to document

00:37:45.179 --> 00:37:47.860
how they're defined differently and rename them separately.

00:37:47.860 --> 00:37:50.820
And to me, that's kind of the first start

00:37:50.820 --> 00:37:52.540
of where I would handle that.

00:37:52.540 --> 00:37:54.260
The second piece is, I think,

00:37:54.260 --> 00:37:56.340
though it's really great at a larger firm

00:37:56.340 --> 00:37:59.699
when you can get kind of to where Matthew was describing,

00:37:59.699 --> 00:38:01.260
like, we're gonna put the data here

00:38:01.260 --> 00:38:02.739
and we're gonna flow it through.

00:38:02.739 --> 00:38:03.580
I think in the meantime,

00:38:03.580 --> 00:38:05.820
you can push out tools and requirements

00:38:05.820 --> 00:38:08.340
to people where they are that meet them where they are.

00:38:08.340 --> 00:38:10.179
So if they start documenting their data,

00:38:10.179 --> 00:38:13.219
it's a lot easier to do that ingestion process.

00:38:13.219 --> 00:38:16.340
Because one of the biggest places I see a lot of this fail

00:38:16.340 --> 00:38:19.939
is when IT or someone tries to start pulling everything in

00:38:19.939 --> 00:38:21.500
and they don't have the business background

00:38:21.500 --> 00:38:22.899
and they don't have the business buy-in,

00:38:22.899 --> 00:38:25.100
they don't get the definitions from the business.

00:38:25.100 --> 00:38:27.260
And then when it comes to being usable,

00:38:27.260 --> 00:38:28.100
the CEO is like,

00:38:28.100 --> 00:38:29.739
your number is different than my people's number.

00:38:29.739 --> 00:38:31.820
I'm just gonna use my people's number.

00:38:31.820 --> 00:38:34.820
And that kind of like turns into a big issue.

00:38:34.820 --> 00:38:37.860
So part of a big piece of it to me is why do they need it?

00:38:37.860 --> 00:38:38.699
Why are they using it?

00:38:38.699 --> 00:38:40.699
And then can we shut it off too?

00:38:40.699 --> 00:38:42.459
It's always a question for me of like,

00:38:42.459 --> 00:38:43.979
does anyone actually read this dashboard?

00:38:43.979 --> 00:38:45.659
Like maybe they're both pulling it,

00:38:45.659 --> 00:38:47.379
creating something and nobody uses it.

00:38:47.379 --> 00:38:48.580
It's just something we've always done.

00:38:48.580 --> 00:38:49.820
So that happens a lot.

00:38:49.820 --> 00:38:51.340
Dan, I don't know if that happens as much to you

00:38:52.179 --> 00:38:53.939
as it happens to me, but.

00:38:53.939 --> 00:38:54.780
Oh, I like that.

00:38:54.780 --> 00:38:56.620
I think it's a really pragmatic answer.

00:38:57.860 --> 00:39:01.500
The way my brain went on this one is big organizations,

00:39:03.179 --> 00:39:04.659
right hand to the left hand

00:39:04.659 --> 00:39:06.260
don't always know what they're doing, right?

00:39:06.260 --> 00:39:11.260
So you may, I think this could easily happen.

00:39:12.620 --> 00:39:13.780
We see it a lot,

00:39:13.780 --> 00:39:15.219
people in this group are doing this thing

00:39:15.219 --> 00:39:16.379
and then people in this other group

00:39:16.379 --> 00:39:17.540
who never talked to each other, right?

00:39:17.540 --> 00:39:18.379
Are doing this other thing

00:39:18.379 --> 00:39:20.979
and turns out the first like eight steps of it

00:39:21.620 --> 00:39:22.620
are exactly the same.

00:39:23.580 --> 00:39:25.459
So here I'm going to say, talk,

00:39:26.939 --> 00:39:30.699
get some organization to be able to,

00:39:30.699 --> 00:39:32.459
you should be able to at least grab a list

00:39:32.459 --> 00:39:35.820
of who has access to the data, right?

00:39:35.820 --> 00:39:38.060
And maybe just have those people come together

00:39:38.060 --> 00:39:40.020
a little bit once a month, once a quarter,

00:39:40.020 --> 00:39:41.659
to be like, hey, this is what we do with the data.

00:39:41.659 --> 00:39:43.139
What do you do with the data?

00:39:43.139 --> 00:39:46.739
And just to start getting people together a little bit,

00:39:46.739 --> 00:39:48.580
because I do believe that no one wants

00:39:48.580 --> 00:39:50.379
to do duplicative work.

00:39:50.860 --> 00:39:54.020
If I feel like as like software engineers,

00:39:54.020 --> 00:39:55.020
growing up through this,

00:39:55.020 --> 00:39:57.060
we're like, if someone's already done it,

00:39:57.060 --> 00:39:59.899
I'm just going to take it and then go from there, right?

00:39:59.899 --> 00:40:02.580
I don't need to like redo these calculations

00:40:02.580 --> 00:40:04.219
that are already done.

00:40:04.219 --> 00:40:07.939
So I think there's some opportunity for collaboration there

00:40:07.939 --> 00:40:09.500
and then just see what makes sense.

00:40:09.500 --> 00:40:12.139
Because sometimes it is duplicative

00:40:12.139 --> 00:40:13.820
and it can be shut off like Jamie's saying.

00:40:13.820 --> 00:40:15.979
And sometimes it's not really,

00:40:15.979 --> 00:40:18.459
and it doesn't work just because of the reality

00:40:18.459 --> 00:40:20.939
of our systems and how we work.

00:40:24.340 --> 00:40:27.260
Yeah, that was going to be my own follow-up question there.

00:40:27.260 --> 00:40:29.219
It's like, how do you know when somebody else

00:40:29.219 --> 00:40:31.419
is doing the same work as you

00:40:31.419 --> 00:40:33.219
somewhere else in the organization?

00:40:34.260 --> 00:40:36.260
Reach, I feel like this is kind of what you do

00:40:36.260 --> 00:40:38.379
with these meetups,

00:40:38.379 --> 00:40:41.100
is if you're in your organization and you're a data scientist,

00:40:41.100 --> 00:40:43.100
you should know the other data scientists.

00:40:43.100 --> 00:40:44.419
If you do BI work,

00:40:44.419 --> 00:40:46.780
you should know the other people that do BI.

00:40:46.780 --> 00:40:48.899
If nothing else, in case your department gets shuttered

00:40:48.899 --> 00:40:51.620
and you need somewhere else to go at a minimum,

00:40:51.620 --> 00:40:53.659
which we're seeing a lot in the industry lately.

00:40:53.659 --> 00:40:57.379
But at a maximum, like knowing what the other people

00:40:57.379 --> 00:40:59.500
that do your type of role across the company do

00:40:59.500 --> 00:41:00.540
is really important.

00:41:00.540 --> 00:41:02.899
And kind of setting up those informational interviews,

00:41:02.899 --> 00:41:05.540
those coffees can help you not just with your data,

00:41:05.540 --> 00:41:06.860
but with your career.

00:41:06.860 --> 00:41:08.139
And it can also create a situation

00:41:08.139 --> 00:41:10.500
where the first time you're coming to someone isn't,

00:41:10.500 --> 00:41:11.699
hey, we make the same thing

00:41:11.699 --> 00:41:13.300
and it's a little bit threatening.

00:41:13.300 --> 00:41:15.300
It's more, oh, we've already talked about this.

00:41:15.300 --> 00:41:16.540
I didn't realize you guys did that,

00:41:17.139 --> 00:41:18.780
but cool, we also do that.

00:41:18.780 --> 00:41:21.699
So I would really recommend making sure

00:41:21.699 --> 00:41:22.739
you have a community.

00:41:22.739 --> 00:41:25.100
A lot of companies do have like, you know,

00:41:25.100 --> 00:41:26.179
little mini groups.

00:41:26.179 --> 00:41:29.100
I know for us, we have a monthly meetup

00:41:29.100 --> 00:41:31.379
of the folks using certain data tools

00:41:31.379 --> 00:41:33.459
that we talk through what we're all working on.

00:41:33.459 --> 00:41:35.860
And that really helps us feel like a team effort

00:41:35.860 --> 00:41:38.060
to get these things slowed down and pulled together

00:41:38.060 --> 00:41:40.219
rather than just like, oh, randomly one day

00:41:40.219 --> 00:41:42.300
you get an email that someone says the thing you're doing

00:41:42.300 --> 00:41:45.219
you shouldn't be doing, which I think can go a long way,

00:41:45.219 --> 00:41:48.139
but also is really beneficial to your own experience

00:41:48.139 --> 00:41:49.419
and the work they're doing

00:41:49.419 --> 00:41:52.020
might help inform other work you're doing.

00:41:52.020 --> 00:41:55.780
So I'd say a lot of that is building that community before

00:41:55.780 --> 00:41:58.139
and thinking about being part of that community.

00:41:59.060 --> 00:41:59.899
Absolutely.

00:41:59.899 --> 00:42:02.500
Yeah, and I just wanna double down on that

00:42:02.500 --> 00:42:05.500
for community organizers who may be on the call.

00:42:05.500 --> 00:42:08.219
And I know a big question for community organizers

00:42:08.219 --> 00:42:11.260
is like, how do we show the value of this community

00:42:11.260 --> 00:42:12.260
to our organization?

00:42:12.260 --> 00:42:14.500
And like what Jamie just said right there,

00:42:14.540 --> 00:42:16.419
that's such a great point and example

00:42:16.419 --> 00:42:18.100
that you could could pull from.

00:42:20.939 --> 00:42:23.020
Chris, I see you just put a question in the chat.

00:42:23.020 --> 00:42:24.340
Wanna jump in here?

00:42:31.300 --> 00:42:32.459
We can't hear you yet.

00:42:32.459 --> 00:42:33.899
You might still be muted.

00:42:35.739 --> 00:42:37.100
I can read it if you want.

00:42:37.100 --> 00:42:39.219
And if you would wanna just add some context

00:42:39.219 --> 00:42:40.820
or jump in after, let me know.

00:42:41.820 --> 00:42:42.860
But the question was,

00:42:42.860 --> 00:42:45.060
would it be in the scope of this meeting

00:42:45.060 --> 00:42:46.780
to talk about possible tools

00:42:46.780 --> 00:42:49.260
that could facilitate data governance?

00:42:49.260 --> 00:42:51.500
Would something like a Git for data

00:42:51.500 --> 00:42:53.219
address some of these issues?

00:43:00.379 --> 00:43:01.219
You want me to go?

00:43:01.219 --> 00:43:04.060
I have a vague answer. Yeah, you can start.

00:43:04.060 --> 00:43:04.899
Hi, Chris.

00:43:04.899 --> 00:43:05.739
Nice to hear from you.

00:43:06.739 --> 00:43:10.179
I'm kind of split on tools here.

00:43:10.179 --> 00:43:11.820
There are tools.

00:43:11.820 --> 00:43:14.939
You know, you can look at their data cataloging tools,

00:43:14.939 --> 00:43:17.020
their data governance tools.

00:43:17.020 --> 00:43:22.020
You could Google this and find a whole list of them.

00:43:22.020 --> 00:43:24.060
And I'd be interested actually for people on the phone

00:43:24.060 --> 00:43:27.699
if they're using things like this, how it's going.

00:43:30.300 --> 00:43:34.580
For me, the need really is to have a tool

00:43:34.699 --> 00:43:37.540
the need really has to be there.

00:43:37.540 --> 00:43:39.860
And the organization really has to see,

00:43:39.860 --> 00:43:42.100
the people doing the work really have to see

00:43:42.100 --> 00:43:43.780
the need for it.

00:43:43.780 --> 00:43:46.139
And I see way too many of these,

00:43:46.139 --> 00:43:49.179
let's implement this data governance tool.

00:43:49.179 --> 00:43:51.500
And then nobody in the organization thinks it's necessary

00:43:51.500 --> 00:43:52.580
and they don't use it.

00:43:52.580 --> 00:43:54.500
And then you just wasted a whole bunch of time

00:43:54.500 --> 00:43:55.620
and money on it.

00:43:56.459 --> 00:43:58.939
So I think you need to do a lot of work

00:43:58.939 --> 00:44:01.540
on generating the need, generating people to do it.

00:44:01.540 --> 00:44:04.459
It's gotta be, you have to start implementing those tools

00:44:05.340 --> 00:44:09.179
at a point where people can't do it by themselves anymore

00:44:09.179 --> 00:44:10.739
and they want this automation

00:44:10.739 --> 00:44:13.939
and they need this automation so that they can do it.

00:44:13.939 --> 00:44:17.100
But to go from, it's kind of a mess right now

00:44:17.100 --> 00:44:21.620
to let's put in whatever data governance tool you want

00:44:21.620 --> 00:44:24.939
is too much of a jump, I think for people.

00:44:26.060 --> 00:44:31.060
Yeah, I would add that I did pop one recent like startup

00:44:31.540 --> 00:44:35.540
that I've seen that's kind of trying to do this.

00:44:35.540 --> 00:44:37.820
But again, one of the things I've talked to them about

00:44:37.820 --> 00:44:39.699
is I don't know what your business case is.

00:44:39.699 --> 00:44:40.739
Like, why do we buy you?

00:44:40.739 --> 00:44:42.780
Because it's just a cost center.

00:44:43.899 --> 00:44:48.899
And so kind of leading off on what Dan was saying,

00:44:50.179 --> 00:44:53.060
it is kind of one of the things I'm seeing

00:44:53.060 --> 00:44:54.780
with a lot of the AI tools

00:44:54.780 --> 00:44:56.459
is that it's kind of getting integrated.

00:44:56.459 --> 00:44:59.620
So it's almost like you don't need your own solution.

00:44:59.620 --> 00:45:00.899
There's a lot more integration,

00:45:00.899 --> 00:45:03.219
it seems like across different platforms that we're using

00:45:03.219 --> 00:45:04.459
where they're adding in features

00:45:04.459 --> 00:45:06.699
that allow you to better govern your data

00:45:06.699 --> 00:45:09.739
as you work with your data in different tools

00:45:09.739 --> 00:45:11.179
like a Databricks or something else.

00:45:11.179 --> 00:45:12.100
Like a lot of these tools,

00:45:12.100 --> 00:45:13.899
DataRobot didn't have like data cleaning

00:45:13.899 --> 00:45:15.739
and data ingestion layers before

00:45:15.739 --> 00:45:17.300
and have added them over the years.

00:45:17.300 --> 00:45:18.139
Not saying they're good,

00:45:18.139 --> 00:45:20.459
I don't wanna advertise those particular ones.

00:45:20.459 --> 00:45:22.620
But we are seeing a lot more stuff

00:45:22.620 --> 00:45:24.780
around like the legacy of your data,

00:45:24.780 --> 00:45:26.219
kind of the lineage of your data,

00:45:26.219 --> 00:45:28.580
all that information becoming more populated

00:45:28.580 --> 00:45:29.459
in a lot of these tools.

00:45:30.300 --> 00:45:31.699
And becoming more visually available.

00:45:31.699 --> 00:45:33.379
So when I think about things you need to know

00:45:33.379 --> 00:45:34.820
about your data to understand it,

00:45:34.820 --> 00:45:36.340
like the distributions and other things,

00:45:36.340 --> 00:45:39.340
a lot of tools are making it much easier to look at that.

00:45:39.340 --> 00:45:41.580
So it's almost less important

00:45:41.580 --> 00:45:44.100
that you're as good as it at the front

00:45:44.100 --> 00:45:46.139
if you are able to check it really easily

00:45:46.139 --> 00:45:47.899
versus having to do a lot of work to check it.

00:45:47.899 --> 00:45:51.659
So I'd be curious how the environment evolves

00:45:51.659 --> 00:45:52.899
over the next couple of years,

00:45:52.899 --> 00:45:55.979
because it feels like a lot of company,

00:45:55.979 --> 00:45:58.979
like tools that we're using for other parts of the process,

00:45:59.500 --> 00:46:01.219
like ML workflows are starting to integrate

00:46:01.219 --> 00:46:02.620
that first section of like,

00:46:02.620 --> 00:46:04.699
oh, wait, the data is actually important.

00:46:04.699 --> 00:46:06.340
It's the core of everything we do.

00:46:06.340 --> 00:46:08.100
So, and I don't know, Dan,

00:46:08.100 --> 00:46:11.659
if at scale you're seeing those types of tools be useful.

00:46:11.659 --> 00:46:13.899
I can see how they'd be useful in a smaller group like mine,

00:46:13.899 --> 00:46:18.899
but maybe for all of Biogen, a little bit more difficult.

00:46:19.219 --> 00:46:20.300
Like you, I'm waiting.

00:46:20.300 --> 00:46:23.939
I think it'll evolve in the next couple of years

00:46:23.939 --> 00:46:24.939
a little bit better.

00:46:25.659 --> 00:46:27.459
Matthew, I see your hand raised.

00:46:27.459 --> 00:46:28.300
Go ahead.

00:46:29.860 --> 00:46:33.860
Yeah, so Dan, I think I agree with you

00:46:33.860 --> 00:46:38.860
for normally for any other tool, but data governance tool,

00:46:39.060 --> 00:46:43.340
because no one in general is going to want to fund

00:46:43.340 --> 00:46:45.260
a data governance tool,

00:46:45.260 --> 00:46:47.860
unless a big data challenge happened

00:46:47.860 --> 00:46:49.659
that cost the company a lot of money.

00:46:50.020 --> 00:46:52.860
And creating a need is also,

00:46:52.860 --> 00:46:56.419
at least I felt in my experience was a challenge

00:46:56.419 --> 00:46:57.260
because again,

00:46:57.260 --> 00:47:00.340
who wants to add additional work to themselves?

00:47:00.340 --> 00:47:05.340
So the way I went about it was,

00:47:05.860 --> 00:47:07.060
let's bring the tool in first,

00:47:07.060 --> 00:47:08.500
because the first question you're gonna get

00:47:08.500 --> 00:47:09.780
when you talk about data governance is,

00:47:09.780 --> 00:47:11.020
well, how are we gonna do it?

00:47:11.020 --> 00:47:12.540
What tools do we have?

00:47:12.540 --> 00:47:14.979
And how much work is it gonna give me?

00:47:14.979 --> 00:47:17.100
And I think that's a really good question.

00:47:17.139 --> 00:47:17.979
What tools do we have?

00:47:17.979 --> 00:47:20.260
And how much work is it gonna give me?

00:47:20.260 --> 00:47:23.179
And my response is, well, we haven't found a tool yet,

00:47:23.179 --> 00:47:25.419
but we do need the data governance.

00:47:25.419 --> 00:47:28.300
Would not work very well.

00:47:28.300 --> 00:47:33.260
So since we utilize Azure for our cloud,

00:47:33.260 --> 00:47:36.939
the tool for us made sense was Azure Purview.

00:47:36.939 --> 00:47:39.659
And more because it's Azure,

00:47:39.659 --> 00:47:40.899
but also because it has integrations

00:47:40.899 --> 00:47:43.459
with many other Azure services.

00:47:43.459 --> 00:47:46.860
And so bringing that tool first in,

00:47:47.620 --> 00:47:50.340
then building a data governance practice around that tool

00:47:50.340 --> 00:47:52.540
worked for our direction again,

00:47:52.540 --> 00:47:55.419
because we don't have to deal with the,

00:47:55.419 --> 00:47:56.260
let's find,

00:47:56.260 --> 00:47:58.500
let's look at all the different platform tools out there

00:47:58.500 --> 00:47:59.500
and try to select one.

00:47:59.500 --> 00:48:02.540
And who's gonna give us a budget to do that?

00:48:02.540 --> 00:48:06.500
Who's going to then benefit from that budget conversation?

00:48:07.780 --> 00:48:10.659
So I think sometimes in rare occasions,

00:48:10.659 --> 00:48:13.379
the tool first works,

00:48:13.379 --> 00:48:16.540
but I do say that I do agree again with you

00:48:17.219 --> 00:48:18.419
for any other tool out there,

00:48:18.419 --> 00:48:19.780
you need to drive the need.

00:48:19.780 --> 00:48:21.300
But I think data governance one is that,

00:48:21.300 --> 00:48:26.100
it's kind of the chicken first before the egg.

00:48:26.100 --> 00:48:28.179
Yeah, and it might be,

00:48:28.179 --> 00:48:29.219
when we say data governance,

00:48:29.219 --> 00:48:31.020
what do we mean exactly on it?

00:48:31.020 --> 00:48:34.780
There's probably some high risk stuff

00:48:34.780 --> 00:48:38.459
that we don't really appreciate at the ground level

00:48:38.459 --> 00:48:42.020
that needs some control and that we just can't,

00:48:42.020 --> 00:48:44.419
you're not gonna find a business case for it.

00:48:44.419 --> 00:48:46.899
There's not gonna be positive ROI for it,

00:48:46.899 --> 00:48:48.300
but it still has to be done.

00:48:49.540 --> 00:48:52.340
And there, I mean,

00:48:52.340 --> 00:48:54.780
maybe you could argue that the need exists already there,

00:48:54.780 --> 00:48:57.860
but it's just not well seen across the organization.

00:48:57.860 --> 00:49:00.500
But I could see that for some like

00:49:00.500 --> 00:49:02.979
overarching kind of approaches.

00:49:03.820 --> 00:49:05.580
This is also a place where I love to go

00:49:05.580 --> 00:49:08.060
to see what regulators are up to.

00:49:08.060 --> 00:49:12.419
So I think some of the biggest drives in insurance

00:49:12.419 --> 00:49:14.979
that I've seen in terms of data cleanup

00:49:14.979 --> 00:49:16.100
have been from things like

00:49:16.100 --> 00:49:18.820
the California right to be forgotten laws.

00:49:18.820 --> 00:49:21.820
So for example, the purpose of that law is that

00:49:21.820 --> 00:49:22.860
if they come to you,

00:49:22.860 --> 00:49:24.939
you have to be able to delete all their data records.

00:49:24.939 --> 00:49:27.219
So that means you have to be able to effectively connect

00:49:27.219 --> 00:49:29.340
all their data records across the org.

00:49:29.340 --> 00:49:32.580
And that is a great justification for data enhancement

00:49:32.580 --> 00:49:34.540
and data tools in a way that is something

00:49:34.540 --> 00:49:36.459
that's very real that the company is facing.

00:49:36.459 --> 00:49:40.699
And we're seeing a lot more stuff coming from the White House

00:49:40.699 --> 00:49:42.939
and from other places and even internationally,

00:49:42.939 --> 00:49:45.260
even more aggressively in Europe, I would say,

00:49:46.219 --> 00:49:49.020
around some of these data governments or data requirements

00:49:49.020 --> 00:49:51.179
or right to be able to see your data

00:49:51.179 --> 00:49:52.459
and the information behind it.

00:49:52.459 --> 00:49:54.540
And a lot of that to me is also

00:49:54.540 --> 00:49:56.020
where we're getting some justification

00:49:56.020 --> 00:49:57.820
for spend in this space is,

00:49:57.820 --> 00:50:00.179
hey, we're gonna get hit with this in the next two years.

00:50:00.179 --> 00:50:01.580
Let's not get fined at the start.

00:50:01.580 --> 00:50:02.820
Let's have this ready.

00:50:02.820 --> 00:50:04.939
And that to me kind of sometimes resonates

00:50:04.939 --> 00:50:06.139
a little bit more as well

00:50:06.139 --> 00:50:07.739
if we're trying to get these tools in place.

00:50:07.739 --> 00:50:11.300
The challenge to me is there isn't a great tool.

00:50:11.300 --> 00:50:13.780
I know like even Informatica,

00:50:13.780 --> 00:50:17.540
which is built just really for that to me is a nightmare.

00:50:19.260 --> 00:50:21.100
Maybe I shouldn't say that on a call.

00:50:22.260 --> 00:50:23.659
An unnamed tool is a nightmare,

00:50:23.659 --> 00:50:26.419
but I haven't seen like a great one either.

00:50:26.419 --> 00:50:27.979
And maybe that's because it's so hard to sell

00:50:27.979 --> 00:50:29.580
in this space historically.

00:50:31.060 --> 00:50:33.300
But it's definitely a challenge on that front too

00:50:33.300 --> 00:50:34.659
of like, what's a good tool?

00:50:34.659 --> 00:50:36.979
I can't like think of one off the top of my head

00:50:36.979 --> 00:50:39.219
that I'm like, I would definitely get that one

00:50:39.219 --> 00:50:41.300
if I had all the money for it.

00:50:41.300 --> 00:50:43.540
Yeah, I think it's maybe for the software companies,

00:50:43.540 --> 00:50:46.139
it's hard for them to position it

00:50:46.139 --> 00:50:48.419
as we change from this centralized governance

00:50:48.419 --> 00:50:50.179
to this mesh governance.

00:50:50.179 --> 00:50:55.020
And like the users of it are more like data scientists

00:50:55.020 --> 00:50:59.739
and data engineers and not like IT DBAs, stuff like that.

00:50:59.739 --> 00:51:03.379
And I think maybe that hasn't caught up yet in the software,

00:51:03.379 --> 00:51:05.540
but I agree with you not necessarily

00:51:05.540 --> 00:51:07.500
to call out specific companies here.

00:51:09.379 --> 00:51:12.939
I think, as you said, regulatory is changing a lot, right?

00:51:13.820 --> 00:51:16.419
Seeing a huge influx the last five or six years

00:51:16.419 --> 00:51:17.979
and more and more requirements.

00:51:17.979 --> 00:51:20.219
And it used to be all about the applications

00:51:21.540 --> 00:51:22.899
and governance on the applications,

00:51:22.899 --> 00:51:24.060
but now it's on the data.

00:51:24.060 --> 00:51:26.139
And now with AI as well, the same thing.

00:51:26.139 --> 00:51:28.540
AI is a data generating machine.

00:51:28.540 --> 00:51:32.219
So we're gonna be seeing a lot more of it.

00:51:33.219 --> 00:51:36.540
I didn't know we were gonna go the tool direction

00:51:36.540 --> 00:51:37.580
in the conversation today,

00:51:37.580 --> 00:51:40.699
but I feel like I should add in here.

00:51:40.699 --> 00:51:43.459
I know a lot of our closet customers

00:51:43.459 --> 00:51:46.100
also work with Databricks for governance,

00:51:46.100 --> 00:51:48.340
regardless of if we're using the term governance

00:51:48.340 --> 00:51:49.179
or stewardship.

00:51:49.179 --> 00:51:52.459
And I just wanted to use the opportunity to add

00:51:52.459 --> 00:51:54.459
that I know a few of our team members

00:51:54.459 --> 00:51:57.419
are gonna be at the summit in a few weeks.

