And I'll ask anybody who if I missed your question

00:55:19.860 --> 00:55:23.860
and you're on right now, if you wanna raise your hand.

00:55:23.860 --> 00:55:27.260
Yeah, there was one I really liked that asked about data

00:55:27.260 --> 00:55:30.060
that changes over time and definitions that change over time

00:55:32.060 --> 00:55:34.139
and how to deal with that.

00:55:34.139 --> 00:55:36.580
And I think, and they asked it as if it was

00:55:36.580 --> 00:55:39.899
a very unique question, but I think it's actually

00:55:39.899 --> 00:55:41.820
a very common question.

00:55:42.100 --> 00:55:45.540
And a big piece of kind of how to think about

00:55:45.540 --> 00:55:46.979
the structure of your data.

00:55:46.979 --> 00:55:49.820
And if you can create flexibility where you can change

00:55:49.820 --> 00:55:52.820
terminology and still have it match and map.

00:55:52.820 --> 00:55:55.260
And a lot of that's like a documentation,

00:55:55.260 --> 00:55:57.179
tagging kind of scenario.

00:55:57.179 --> 00:56:00.060
So I was really excited and interested about that one.

00:56:00.060 --> 00:56:03.219
I just wanted to call out that that's a very common issue.

00:56:03.219 --> 00:56:08.219
And also you can create a framework for that.

00:56:08.260 --> 00:56:12.459
And also you can create a framework for your data

00:56:12.459 --> 00:56:14.139
where if the name of something is changing

00:56:14.139 --> 00:56:17.540
you can still have it linked back to the historical names.

00:56:17.540 --> 00:56:19.219
And I think that's something that's important to know.

00:56:19.219 --> 00:56:21.699
I know we don't have time to dive into the logistics of it

00:56:21.699 --> 00:56:23.620
but I don't know, Dan, if you have additional comments

00:56:23.620 --> 00:56:25.699
on that one, but that one really caught my eye.

00:56:25.699 --> 00:56:26.540
Yeah, that one was interesting.

00:56:26.540 --> 00:56:30.340
Cause they're like, I managed data over like 50 years

00:56:30.340 --> 00:56:31.179
or something like that.

00:56:31.179 --> 00:56:33.540
And over the 50 years, it changes.

00:56:33.540 --> 00:56:35.100
Maybe I'm the only one who has this problem

00:56:35.100 --> 00:56:37.659
and we're all like, no, everyone has this problem.

00:56:39.060 --> 00:56:42.459
That it's a longer conversation for sure.

00:56:42.459 --> 00:56:46.580
My gut is to always say, be pragmatic here

00:56:46.580 --> 00:56:48.459
and understand there is a reality.

00:56:48.459 --> 00:56:49.860
It does change.

00:56:49.860 --> 00:56:51.300
We have something with like vendors

00:56:51.300 --> 00:56:52.979
and vendors get bought by other companies

00:56:52.979 --> 00:56:54.459
and we're trying to match.

00:56:54.459 --> 00:56:56.020
We have the name of the old company

00:56:56.020 --> 00:56:58.820
and then they don't exist anymore, but it's the new company.

00:56:58.820 --> 00:57:01.260
It's a, how do you manage that over time?

00:57:01.260 --> 00:57:03.659
It is challenging and you need standards,

00:57:03.659 --> 00:57:07.419
you need process to be able to do that.

00:57:07.419 --> 00:57:09.820
But you just need to make some decisions too.

00:57:09.820 --> 00:57:11.820
Say, we're no longer doing it like that.

00:57:11.820 --> 00:57:14.100
We're doing it like this now.

00:57:14.100 --> 00:57:17.300
Because otherwise you just get stuck in this gray area

00:57:17.300 --> 00:57:19.260
where no one can go forward

00:57:19.260 --> 00:57:22.340
and everyone's doing stuff a little bit differently.

00:57:22.340 --> 00:57:23.979
Ties back nicely to your first point

00:57:23.979 --> 00:57:25.659
of why are we using this?

00:57:25.659 --> 00:57:27.899
And I say that as someone who uses 50 years of data

00:57:27.899 --> 00:57:29.219
back when I was in life insurance,

00:57:29.219 --> 00:57:31.659
but there's always the question of,

00:57:31.659 --> 00:57:33.459
is this part of the business still relevant?

00:57:33.459 --> 00:57:35.260
Is this historical name still relevant?

00:57:35.260 --> 00:57:37.300
Do we still need this?

00:57:38.060 --> 00:57:39.459
And sometimes it's hard to realize that

00:57:39.459 --> 00:57:42.060
when you're in the thick of fixing the data.

